Creating a function to reduce the memory of dataframe¶

In [2]:
def reduce_mem_usage(train_data):
    start_mem = train_data.memory_usage().sum() / 1024**2
    
    for col in train_data.columns:
        col_type = train_data[col].dtype

        if not pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(train_data[col]):
            # Handle non-numeric columns (e.g., object, datetime) appropriately
            # You might choose to skip these columns or apply a different logic
            continue
        
        if pd.api.types.is_categorical_dtype(train_data[col]):
            train_data[col] = train_data[col].cat.as_ordered()
        else:
            c_min = train_data[col].min()
            c_max = train_data[col].max()

            if pd.api.types.is_integer_dtype(train_data[col]):
                # Handle integer types
                if c_min > np.iinfo(np.int8).min and c_max < np.iinfo(np.int8).max:
                    train_data[col] = train_data[col].astype(np.int8)
                elif c_min > np.iinfo(np.int16).min and c_max < np.iinfo(np.int16).max:
                    train_data[col] = train_data[col].astype(np.int16)
                elif c_min > np.iinfo(np.int32).min and c_max < np.iinfo(np.int32).max:
                    train_data[col] = train_data[col].astype(np.int32)
                elif c_min > np.iinfo(np.int64).min and c_max < np.iinfo(np.int64).max:
                    train_data[col] = train_data[col].astype(np.int64)
            elif pd.api.types.is_float_dtype(train_data[col]):
                # Handle float types
                if c_min > np.finfo(np.float16).min and c_max < np.finfo(np.float16).max:
                    train_data[col] = train_data[col].astype(np.float16)
                elif c_min > np.finfo(np.float32).min and c_max < np.finfo(np.float32).max:
                    train_data[col] = train_data[col].astype(np.float32)
                else:
                    train_data[col] = train_data[col].astype(np.float64)

    end_mem = train_data.memory_usage().sum() / 1024**2
    print(f'Memory usage of dataframe is {start_mem:.2f} MB --> {end_mem:.2f} MB (Decreased by {100 * (start_mem - end_mem) / start_mem:.1f}%)')

    return train_data

orders = dd.read_csv(root_csv + 'orders.csv')
departments = dd.read_csv(root_csv + 'departments.csv')
aisles = dd.read_csv(root_csv + 'aisles.csv')
products = dd.read_csv(root_csv + 'products.csv')
order_products_train = dd.read_csv(root_csv + 'order_products_train.csv')
order_products_prior = dd.read_csv(root_csv + 'order_products_prior.csv')

Concatenating all dataframes into single unified dataframe for data analysis¶

In [4]:
# Concatenate DataFrames along rows
order_products = dd.concat([order_products_prior, order_products_train], axis=0)

# Merge DataFrames using Dask
order_products = dd.merge(order_products, products, on='product_id', how='left')
order_products = dd.merge(order_products, aisles, on='aisle_id', how='left')
order_products = dd.merge(order_products, departments, on='department_id', how='left')
order_products = dd.merge(order_products, orders, on='order_id', how='left')

# Compute the result to obtain a Pandas DataFrame
order_products = order_products.compute()

# Creating a pickle file for unified datafrane
order_products.to_pickle(root_pickle + 'order_products.pkl')

# Reducing memory of unified dataframe
reduce_mem_usage(order_products)

plt.show()

Most Popular Products on different days¶

In [25]:
prod_day_EDA = order_products.groupby(['order_dow', 'product_name']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
prod_day_EDA = prod_day_EDA.sort_values(['order_dow', 'counts'], ascending=[True, False])
prod_day_EDA = prod_day_EDA.groupby('order_dow').head(5).reset_index(drop = True)
ax = sns.catplot(x="order_dow", y="counts", hue="product_name", data=prod_day_EDA, kind="bar", legend=False)
ax.add_legend(title="Product")
ax.set_axis_labels("Day of Week", "Total Orders of Most Frequent Products")
ax.fig.suptitle("Most Popular Products on different Days of Week", va="baseline", ha="center")
ax.savefig("Most Popular Products on Different Days of Week.png")
